name: Deer Medallion Necklace
description:
Schloss Banz Necklace available to ship!

The deer head on this necklace is actually a hiking medallion from the 1940’s. Hiking medallions would have been mounted on a walking or hiking stick with two or three nails to show the places a person had visited.

This specific medallion is from Schloss Banz. Schloss is the German word for “castle”. Schloss Banz is also known as Banz Abbey, a former Benedictine monastery in Germany. Countess Alberada and her husband Count Hermann of Habsberg-Kastl founded it in 1070, when only members of nobility were accepted as monks.

Because each Hiking medallion I have is from a different German, Bavarian or Bolivian location, each necklace will be one-of-a-kind. I will send photos of your unique necklace before shipping. 

All necklaces are made to order. Please allow up to 30 days for me to make the necklace, send photos, receive confirmation from you and finally to ship. 



**PLEASE NOTE: The Harz necklace shown has been SOLD, however, I have many more deer head medallions that look just like this, but they are all from different locations. I will include a detailed history of your one-of-a-kind medallion! I will also send photos of your necklace before shipping. Thanks!

Harz History: The center piece on the necklace shown is a vintage hiking medallion from Harz, the highest mountain range in Northern Germany. The name Harz derives from the Middle High German word Hardt or Hart which means mountain forest. The Harz is home to the legendary summit, Brocken which rises 3,744 ft above sea level and the famous peak, Wurmberg which towers 3,186 ft above Lower Saxony. I cannot be certain of the exact age of the medallion, though it dates somewhere between 1940 and 1960.**

name: Arabesque Damascene Pen Knife Necklace
description:
Damascene is the art of interlacing gold on iron or steel to produce beautiful decorative designs that has become the trademark of Toledo, Spain. It has roots in the Middle Ages and originates from the oriental-style artisan work done in Damascus, Syria. The craft, perfected by the Arabs and brought with them to Spain, has remained virtually unchanged over the centuries, and practiced also by Egyptians, Greeks, and Romans. Around the XV century damascene became popular in Europe, and Toledo, Spain became famous worldwide for producing such works of art.

This necklace features a damascene knife from 1972, oxidized steel with a beautiful gold arabesque motif inlay. TOLEDO is engraved on the knife blade - meaning this was authentically crafted in Toledo, Spain. Rostfrei is also engraved in the blade - this is German for “rust free” which means the blades are stainless steel. 
Please be advised that this IS a knife. Do NOT take it on a plane, or into places where such things are restricted. Do not use it for negative purposes.
 
18-24 karat gold inlay on oxidized steel.

name: Japanese Pygmy Lighter Necklace
description:
This miniature lighter is about 3/4 of an inch small. It was made in Japan in the 1950s, shortly after the occupation of the Allied Nations. Japan was known for their "pygmy" lighters, which were manufactured in Japan and shipped all over the world. Many lighters had hand painted enamel scenes like this one.

The scene depicted on this lighter is that of one of the famous Shinto Shrines and Mount Fuji, there is also a small traditional Japanese sailboat, cherry blossoms and the Chureito Pagoda can be seen on the far left side of Mt. Fuji, under the cherry blossoms. On the back is an enamel japanese dragon. It still has it's original bells!

The lighter is in mint condition, only a new flint and lighter fluid is needed for it to work. When working, do not use for long periods of time, since the casing is metal they tend to get hot.

name: Japanese Ozarks Miniature Lighter
description:
This miniature lighter is about 3/4 of an inch small. It was made in Japan in the 1950s, shortly after the occupation of the Allied Nations. Japan was known for their "pygmy" lighters, which were manufactured in Japan and shipped all over the world. Many lighters had hand painted enamel scenes like this one.

This was a souvenir lighter for the Ozarks, a highland region in the United States that occupies northwestern Oklahoma and southeastern Kansas.

At first, I thought the pretty pink flowers depicted on the lighter may be cherry blossoms, but after further research, I realized cherry blossoms have more than 4 petals and are not native to the Ozarks. I discovered the blossoms are actually Ozark Persimmons. They grow abundant and wild in this area of the United States. Persimmons develop their sweet taste in the winter.

The lighter hangs on a decorative silver chain about 28 inches long from end to end. The lighter will be shipped without lighter fluid due to strict shipping policies. One you receive it, fill it up with fluid and it should be ready to go!

description:
he medallion on this necklace is from an old pocket watch. There is a vintage Bulova women's watch face on the pocket watch movement. It hangs on a thick silver tone chain - 23 inches from end to end - the pendant falls right below the center bottom of your ribcage.

Bulova is a luxury watch and clocks manufacturer in Woodside, Queens, NY. The face on this watch is dated between 1925 and 1945.

Fun fact: Bulova paid $9 for the world's 1st TV commercial, placed July 1, 1941 before a baseball game between Brooklyn Dodgers and Philadelphia Phillies.

name: Bulova 21 Jewel Watch Movement Ring
description:
A little history lesson: in 1875 Joseph Bulova, a 23-year-old Czech immigrant, opened a small jewelry shop on Maiden Lane in New York City, where his watch company became known for making high quality pocket watches and clocks. Come 1919 During World War I, the convenience of wristwatches (as opposed to pocket watches) is discovered - it was easier for soldiers to check the time if the watch was on their wrist instead of tucked away in their pockets. Therefore, Bulova introduces the first full line of men's jeweled wristwatches. 1924 - Bulova unveils the first full line of ladies' watches.

This particular watch movement is from the 1930's. it has 21 jewels which means, throughout the movement there are 21 rubies which were used instead of metal to help the gears run smoothly without sticking.

The movement is silver with gold accents and is mounted on a silver adjustable filigree ring.

name: Freeze Time Rensie Watch Face Ring
description:
Amongst my collection of small ornate watch faces, I will sometimes find a beauty like this one that would make a perfect ring.

Rensie is a very elusive watch company. Through my research I have discovered that watches by the name of Rensie were built with Swiss made parts and assembled in Germany, post WWII.

name: Vintage Watch Movement Ring
description:
I've always been fascinated with the complex inner operations of clocks and watches, so i began collecting antique watch parts, faces, gears and movements. 

All of my small watch treasures date between the mid 1800's to the mid 1900's when watches were made with quality and heart. Often the insides of the watches are more beautiful than than the surface. I wanted to share this discovery with everyone.

This particular ring features an Elgin women's watch movement from 1936. Elgin National Watch Co. was the largest U.S. watch manufacturer located in Elgin, Illinois. They produced watches from 1864 - 1964.

This copper tone ring is adjustable and ready to ship!
